replies.body:
@Greatdeathz

Considering 10 cent (the company that owns riot) posted the highest profits out of any games company in the world this year, and league of legends is the most played game worldwide, you would hope that the constant complaints about the toxic nature of our community would actually yield some sort of results. Games that have far smaller player bases and draw in far less money manage to have active admins and moderators, and its quite obvious that the current system of reporting and automated bans is totally ineffective. Its also noteworthy that we all agree to 'the summoners code', an electronic contract. contracts are two way binding legally binding documents, if were bound to follow the code, riot should be bound to enforce it properly. 

A game as widely loved as this would have no shortage of volunteers that would be willing to pitch in and act as a tribunal, but it seems like it impacts 10 cents bottom line too much to manage this. It feels like it wont be until the game is so toxic that it starts to go into decline that anything will actually happen, which is quite sad because its such a good game.
